FNOL processes are lengthy and cumbersome, requiring customers to fill out complex forms and follow up multiple times, while insurers struggle with incomplete or inconsistent intake data. The solution begins with the Policyholder experience, where the customer can initiate a claim through an Intelligent FNOL interface.

With this AI-orchestrated claims solution, the policyholder simply describes the incident using voice or text. In this example, the customer reports stating There was a major burst pipe in the kitchen that damaged the floor and cabinets. As soon as the narration is submitted, the AI automatically identifies the incident as a property damage claim and extracts insights and system immediately presents a structured key details of what the customer reported along with the cause of loss, affected areas, incident timeline, and severity indicators. Along with policy information that is autofilled from the policy admin system. Now clicking on confirm and continue

This creates a faster, more accurate, and customer-friendly FNOL experience while reducing manual intake efforts for the insurer.
Before submission there is an intake validation from the system by asking contexual questions, once done policyholder can upload an image or videos as an evidence.
Prefilled FNOL report will be generated with corresponding sections, now he can review and confirm the AI fields to submit the FNOL, after which claims number is generated.
Tracking claims would enable policy holder to see the interactive claim journey he can raise any concerns if required which flows to the adjuster.

The claim is then routed to the Adjuster Portal, where the adjuster can see claims related insights and he clicks on follow my claims to see all the claims that have to be reviewed opening the particular claim gives an insights related to customer and he can request more information schedule interview or respond to escalation, Now adjuster opens loss adjustments page where he gets detailed insights of customer documents, verification insights, vendor assigned if any, also he can directly go to the document hub to view documents and system automatically classifies it providing insights, here he can approve or reject the documents that has been provided, and the adjuster can conclude the Intake validation, now the claim moves to loss Investigation stage , now the adjuster completes the investigation to move forward and any point in time he can ask for additional documents from the Policyholder, the AI-assisted assessment. Here, the platform validates coverage eligibility, evaluates fraud indicators, and recommends reserve amounts, repair-versus-replacement guidance, and settlement recommendations.




Now he moves to AI-assisted Loss assessment for that particular claim running the AI analysis generates a summary of loss, deductible, amount and more displaying loss calculation engine and repair versus replacement recommendation. The same section gives a delayed view of the recommendation for repair and replacement. Moving back to loss assessment and Running AI analysis for AI to recommend approval or rejection so as the fraud indicator detects low, so it will not directly redirected to SIU, Although the platform supports Straight Through Processing, or STP, human oversight remains central to the process. Even when the AI recommends automated approval, the adjuster retains full authority to approve, reject, or escalate the claim for further investigation. If suspicious indicators or inconsistencies are detected, the claim can be escalated to the Special Investigation Unit, or SIU. Claims with fraud scores above the defined threshold are automatically flagged for SIU review, though adjusters can manually escalate any claim when necessary.  Here, the platform validates coverage eligibility, evaluates fraud indicators, and recommends reserve amounts, repair-versus-replacement guidance, and settlement recommendations.

Once forwarded, the claim appears in the SIU portal, after loging in investigators can review claim timelines, request additional documentation, schedule interviews, or trigger external verification processes. The system also tracks SLA timelines to ensure investigations remain within compliance windows.

After review, the SIU can clear the claim and return it to the adjuster for further processing. Throughout this process, claim statuses, investigation outcomes, and pending customer actions are continuously updated and reflected across the platform.

Once the investigation is cleared, the adjuster logs in and views latest actions of that particular claim and in loss assessment he proceeds with claim approval. The platform confirms coverage limits, fraud assessment outcomes, and approval decisions while maintaining a complete audit trail of human and AI-assisted actions.

Following approval, the system activates Smart Vendor Matching. Using AI-driven Vendor Intelligence Scores, the platform automatically recommends the most suitable vendor for the repair work. The recommendation considers multiple factors, including skill specialization, licensing compliance, SLA performance, cost versus peer, capacity, rework rates, subrogation potential, and more.

The adjuster can accept the AI recommendation or manually select another vendor if required.

The platform also supports Drone Verification Intelligence. Before final approval, adjusters can compare customer-uploaded images with drone imagery to validate the extent of the damage. AI-driven visual verification confirms alignment, detects discrepancies, identifies structural defects, and even validates whether uploaded images are authentic and not AI-generated.

Next, the experience moves to the Vendor Management Portal. Vendor managers can monitor active vendors, manage onboarding requests, approve or reject new vendor applications, and track vendor performance across multiple dimensions.

The platform provides visibility into vendor SLA compliance, cost deviations, rework rates, licensing risks, and operational performance. Vendors with poor performance or compliance concerns can be automatically flagged or deactivated, ensuring only qualified vendors remain eligible for assignments.
New Vendors can also be onboarded and can be approved.

The Vendor Performance Dashboard highlights top-performing vendors, identifies at-risk vendors, and provides AI-generated operational insights to support smarter vendor governance decisions.
Vendors assignments section provides assignment details.
Risk and Compliance displays active vendors and AI signals, suspicious billing patterns, License validation of vendors.
Moving to Vendor SLA tracker screen , displays SLA compliant vendors and the reason.  

Another key capability is the AI-powered Document Hub. Rather than functioning as a passive repository, the Document Hub acts as a centralized intelligent workspace for all claim-related documentation.

Documents uploaded by policyholders, vendors, or adjusters are automatically classified, tagged, and processed using AI-powered extraction models. The platform extracts structured information such as repair estimates, affected property areas, costs, inspection findings, and supporting evidence.

Adjusters can instantly access claim summaries, extracted insights, original images, drone verification outputs, and document intelligence from a single interface, significantly reducing manual review efforts and improving claim transparency.

In summary, this AI-orchestrated property and motor claims solution transforms the traditional claims lifecycle into an intelligent, customer-centric experience. The platform combines Intelligent FNOL, AI-assisted assessment, proactive SIU investigation, centralized document intelligence, smart vendor orchestration, and automated verification capabilities into a unified ecosystem.

The result is faster settlements, reduced operational costs, lower claims leakage, improved adjuster productivity, and enhanced customer satisfaction — all while ensuring humans remain at the center of every critical decision, augmented by AI-driven intelligence and automation.

